  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions can be traced through several key developments:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Initially addressed through tax evasion and banking regulations\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First comprehensive anti-money laundering (AML) legislation\n- Established reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Required documentation of large cash transactions\n\n3. International Progression:\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a serious criminal issue\n- Vienna Convention (1988) - First international treaty addressing money laundering in drug trafficking context\n\n4. Major Milestone - BCCI Scandal:\n- 1991 international banking scandal exposed massive money laundering operations\n- Prompted significant regulatory reforms globally\n\n5. Key Legislation:\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Expanded AML provisions post-9/11\n- Enhanced international information sharing and enforcement\n\n6. Global Standardization:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Created international standards and recommendations for combating money laundering\n\n7. Continuous Evolution:\n- Ongoing refinement of legal frameworks\n- Increasing technological complexity of financial crimes",
